useEffect-Hook
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The useEffect hook in React is used to run code (side effects) when dependencies change, when the component renders, or when the component mounts (loads).

Here are some common use cases for useEffect:

- Fetching data from an API
- Setting up timers
- Listening to browser events
- Updating the document title
- Manually interacting with the DOM
- Subscribing to and unsubscribing from services
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Example:
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
useEffect(()=>{
console.log("Hello World")
}, [])

The useEffect hook takes two arguments. The first argument is an arrow function containing the side-effect logic. The second argument is a dependency array that controls when the 
effect runs.

In the example above, the useEffect hook runs once after the component is mounted because the dependency array is empty. It prints "Hello World" once and is not executed again.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
useEffect(()=>{
console.log("Hello World")
}, )

As we can see in the code above, the dependency array is missing. If we don’t provide a dependency array, the effect runs after every re-render of the component. 
Every time the effect runs, "Hello World" is printed.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
